Unrestrained Central Bank Governors?
PRAGUE – Recently, there has been a one-sided criticism of central banks in advanced economies that has gained traction.
The main points of attack are roughly as follows: since 2008, monetary policymakers have become too active, expanding their powers too quickly, and are endangering the economy.
This view – which, curiously, is popular among ideologically opposed camps, such as liberals and neo-Marxists – is fundamentally wrong.
Critics fail to grasp that modern central banks must not only contain inflation but also ensure long-term price stability.
Price levels are like human body temperature, fluctuating within a range without being too high or too low without causing serious symptoms.
To combat deflation caused by weak demand and to curb high inflation driven by excessive demand, central banks must be equally "active."
Despite the battle being fully symmetric, public perception of it is strangely skewed, especially in countries where people are financially conservative.
This includes my home country, the Czech Republic. Czech savers save on a small scale, and the loan-to-deposit ratio is still far below 100%.
The Czechs are worried about inflation, even though the inflation rate last year reached a 13-year low, and the National Bank of the Czech Republic, of which I have served as deputy governor since 2013, has been working to eliminate deflation risks.
<s>Other common complaints about central bank policies since 2008 are that they create redistribution effects.
<s>Of course they do, so what?
<s>Any monetary policy action redistributes wealth.
<s>Raising interest rates makes savers happy, while cutting rates benefits borrowers.
<s>Importers prefer a strong exchange rate; exporters prefer a weak one.
<s>To be effective, monetary policy must have different effects on different groups at different times.
<s>This is not a mistake; this is the nature of monetary policy.
<s>Some critics say that central banks have failed to meet their inflation targets, so their activism was neither necessary nor effective.
<s>Sometimes they even combine these contradictory criticisms in a single sentence, as if they were accusing someone of firing blanks and then causing casualties.
<s>The reality is that central banks in advanced economies have succeeded in maintaining price stability and purchasing power during and after the global financial crisis – and they did it with outstanding success.
<s>If it were not for their intervention, their economies would have faced catastrophic deflation, sharp falls in asset prices, and a complete collapse of both financial and real sectors.
<s>Clearly, strong action was the right thing to do (the role of the central banks in the onset of the crisis is a separate issue).
<s>In a system using non-intrinsic-value elastic currency, for purchasing power to remain broadly stable over time, the quantity of money must change.
<s>Therefore, price stability, rather than the quantity of money, is what matters.
<s>The expansion of central bank balance sheets reflects the depth of the problems faced by many economies after 2008.
<s>In this context, central banks took necessary measures to maintain purchasing power and price stability.
<s>For them, there is no "activism"; only the mission that needs to be achieved in the long term.
<s>If you find this assertion arrogant, let me provide some evidence.
<s>Voters vote with their wallets.
<s>If their purchasing power suffered significantly after 2008, they naturally sought to replace their currency (with other currencies, precious metals, or other savings methods).
This is rare in developed economies.
Of course, many central banks have not met their inflation targets.
(Central banks typically define the ideal economic "temperature" as annual inflation around 2%.
) This is undoubtedly unpleasant, but it does not lead to disaster, especially considering that some price declines stem from supply — not demand — shocks, such as the plummeting oil prices.
This shock benefits consumers and poses no threat to price stability, at least for oil importers.
<s>Consider this scenario.
<s>A company plans to increase its sales by 2%, but the manager achieves this by increasing sales by 1% each of the next two years.
<s>Would you consider this company a failure?
<s>No, probably not.
<s>After all, private companies often have a deviation of 10% or more between planned and actual profits and revenues.
<s>The variables affecting most businesses are fewer than those affecting central banks.
<s>Given that, how can you expect central banks to achieve precise inflation targets regardless of the economic environment?
<s>It must be clarified that I am not saying central banks should not strive to achieve their targets.
<s>They should absolutely do so.
<s>Furthermore, they should absolutely not allow inflation expectations to become unstable.
However, when evaluating central banks, people need to maintain proper perspective.
They need to stop saying things that are not true — such as the idea that central banks' policy arsenal is not only exhausted but nearly empty.
Moneymaking policymakers have ample weapons and unlimited ammunition to use at their discretion.
These weapons come in different calibers and have varying degrees of effectiveness at different times.
Not all weapons are suitable for every economy and every situation.
But central banks' ability to create and destroy money is theoretically unlimited.
Central bankers should tell the ignorant critics enough is enough.
Our critics cannot explain in a clear and credible way why price stability is a wrong target, what key objectives the central banks should pursue, and what utterly different approach they should have taken since 2008.
The reason for this is simple: the approach taken by developed economies' central banks since the crisis was the right one.
In fact, this approach pulled our economies back from the brink.
You're welcome.
